</exercise> 

<exercise>
  <task>
    <statement>
      <p>
        Give the parametric form of a line that goes through the points <m>(1,2,3)</m> and <m>(4,5,6)</m>.
      </p>
    </statement>
    <solution>
      <p>
        <m>\vr(t)= \langle 1,2,3 \rangle +t \langle 3,3,3 \rangle</m>, but remember that we could use other base points or any vector that is parallel to the direction vector given here.
      </p>
    </solution>
  </task>
  <task>
    <statement>
      <p>
        Do the lines given by <m>\overrightarrow{r}_1(t)=\langle 0,1,1 \rangle + t\langle 1,2,2 \rangle </m> and <m>\overrightarrow{r}_2(t)=\langle 2,0,3 \rangle + t\langle 1,4,4 \rangle </m> intersect? If so, state at what point(s) they intersect.
      </p>
    </statement>
    <solution>
      <p>
        By setting the components of the two equations equal, we can see if there is a t and s value that will correspond to a common point between these lines. Algebraically, this means we need to solve the equations <m>t=2+s</m>, <m>1+2t=4s</m>, and <m>1+2t=3+4s</m>. This system of equations does not have a solution, so there is no point of intersection. 
      </p>
    </solution>
  </task>
  <task>
    <statement>
      <p>
        Give a parametric form of the y-axis.
      </p>
    </statement>
    <solution>
      <p>
        <m>\vr(t) = \langle 0,t,0 \rangle </m>
      </p>
    </solution>
  </task>
  <task>
    <statement>
      <p>
        Give a parametric form of a line that does not intersect the xz-plane.
      </p>
    </statement>
    <solution>
      <p>
        Any line that does not intersect the xz-plane cannot have a y coordinate of zero, for example <m>\vr(t) = \langle 1+2t, 2, 3-t \rangle </m> or <m>\vr(t) = \langle 6,-2,5+2t \rangle </m>.
      </p>
    </solution>
  </task>
  <task>
    <statement>
      <p>
        Give a parametric form for the line that goes through points given by <m>x=2y=3z</m>.
      </p>
    </statement>
    <hint>
      <p>
        Find two points that would satisfy these equations.
      </p>
    </hint>
    <solution>
      <p>
        This line will go through the origin as well as the point <m>(6,3,2)</m>. Thus a parameterization could be given by <m> \vr(t)=\langle 6t,3t,2t \rangle</m>. 
      </p>
    </solution>
  </task>
</exercise>

  <exercise xml:id="Ez_9_5_1">
    <introduction>
      <p>
        The vector and parametric forms of a line allow us to easily describe line segments in space.
      </p>

      <p>
        Let <m>P_1 = (1,2,-1)</m> and <m>P_2 = (-2,1,-2)</m>, and let <m>\mathcal{L}</m> be the line in <m>\R^3</m> through <m>P_1</m> and <m>P_2</m> as in <xref ref="ActLines3D1">Activity</xref>.        
      </p>
    </introduction>
    <task>
      <statement>
        <p>
          What value of the parameter <m>t</m> makes <m>(x(t), y(t), z(t)) = P_1</m>? What value of <m>t</m> makes <m>(x(t), y(t), z(t)) = P_2</m>?
        </p>
      </statement>
      <answer>
        <p>
          The parameter <m>t</m> that makes <m>(x(t), y(t), z(t)) = P_1</m> is <m>t = 0</m>. The parameter <m>t</m> that makes <m>(x(t), y(t), z(t)) = P_2</m> is <m>t = 1</m>.
        </p>
      </answer>
      <solution>
        <p>
          From activity 9.5.2, <m>\overrightarrow{P_0P_1} = \langle -3, -1, -1 \rangle</m>. The vector form of the line through <m>P_1</m> and <m>P_2</m> is <m>\vr(t) = \langle 1, 2, -1\rangle + t * \langle-3, -1, -1\rangle</m>. Using parametric equations, this is equal to <m>x(t) = 1 - 3t, y(t) = 2 - t, z(t) = -1 - t</m>.
        </p>

        <p>
          To find the corresponding t-values for each point, set each coordinate equal to the corresponding parametric equation. <m>1 = 1 - 3t, 2 = 2 - t, -1 = -1 -t</m>. Solve each equation to get <m>t = 0</m>. For <m>P_2, -2 = 1 - 3t, 1 = 2 - t, -2 = -1 - t</m>. Solve each equation to get <m>t = 1</m>. 
        </p>
      </solution>
    </task>
    <task>
      <statement>
        <p>
          What <m>t</m> values describe the line segment between the points <m>P_1</m> and <m>P_2</m>?
        </p>
      </statement>
      <answer>
        <p>
          The line segment between points <m>P_1</m> and <m>P_2</m> is defined by <m>0 \leq t \leq 1</m>.
        </p>
      </answer>
      <solution>
        <p>
          All the points between <m>P_1</m> and <m>P_2</m> will have <m>t</m>-values between <m>t = 0</m> and <m>t = 1</m>. Therefore, the line segment between <m>P_1</m> and <m>P_2</m> is defined for <m>0 \leq t \leq 1</m>.
        </p>
      </solution>
    </task>
    <task>
      <statement>
        <p>
          What about the line segment (along the same line) from <m>(7,4,1)</m> to <m>(-8,-1,-4)</m>?
        </p>
      </statement>
      <answer>
        <p>
          The line segment between points <m>(7, 4, 1)</m> and <m>(-8, -1, -4)</m> is defined by <m>-2 \leq t \leq 3</m>.
        </p>
      </answer>
      <solution>
        <p>
          For <m>P_3, 7 = 1 - 3t, 4 = 2 - t, 1 = -1 -t</m>. Solve each equation to get <m>t = -2</m>. For <m>P_4, -8 = 1 - 3t, -1 = 2 - t, -4 = -1 - t</m>. Solve each equation to get <m>t = 3</m>. 
        </p>
        <p>
          Therefore, line segment between points <m>(7, 4, 1)</m> and <m>(-8, -1, -4)</m> is defined by <m>-2 \leq t \leq 3</m>.
        </p>
      </solution>
    </task>
    <task>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Now, consider a segment that lies on a different line:  parameterize the segment that connects point <m>R=(4,-2,7)</m> to <m>Q=(-11,4,27)</m> in such a way that <m>t = 0</m> corresponds to point <m>Q</m>, while <m>t = 2</m> corresponds to <m>R</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <answer>
        <p>
          <m>x(t) = -11 + \frac{15}{2}t, y(t) = 4 - 3t, z(t) = 17 + 5t</m>.
        </p>
      </answer>
      <solution>
        <p>
          <m>\overrightarrow{QR} = \langle 15, -6, -20 \rangle</m>. We need to find a scalar (direction) vector in the direction of <m>\langle 15, -6, -20 \rangle</m>. If point <m>Q</m> is the initial point, then <m>\vr(t) = \langle -11, 4, 27 \rangle + t * \langle 15v, -6v, -20v \rangle</m>. When <m>t = 2, \langle 4, -2, 7 \rangle = \langle -11, 4, 27 \rangle + (2) * \langle 15v, -6v, -20v \rangle</m>. Solve for <m>v</m> to get <m>v = \frac{1}{2}</m>.
        </p>
        <p>
          Therefore, <m>\vr(t) = \langle -11, 4, 27 \rangle + t * \langle 15 * \frac{1}{2} , -6 * \frac{1}{2}, -20 * \frac{1}{2} \rangle</m>. This cooresponds to parametric equations <m>x(t) = -11 + \frac{15}{2}t, y(t) = 4 - 3t, z(t) = 27 -10t</m>.
        </p>
      </solution>
    </task> 
  </exercise>

  <exercise xml:id="Ez_9_5_2">
    <introduction>
      <p>
        This exercise explores key relationships between a pair of lines. Consider the following two lines: one with parametric equations <m>x(s) = 4-2s</m>, <m>y(s) = -2 + s</m>, <m>z(s) = 1 + 3s</m>, and the other being the line through <m>(-4, 2, 17)</m> in the direction <m>\vv = \langle -2, 1, 5 \rangle</m>.
      </p>
    </introduction>
    <task>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Find a direction vector for the first line, which is given in parametric form.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <answer>
        <p>
          <m>\langle -2, 1, 3 \rangle</m>.
        </p>
      </answer>
      <solution>
        <p>
          Identify the coefficients in front of the <m>s</m> terms. <m>\langle -2, 1, 3 \rangle</m>.
        </p>
      </solution>
    </task>
    <task>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Find parametric equations for the second line, written in terms of the parameter <m>t</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <answer>
        <p>
          <m>x(t) = -4 - 2t, y(t) = 2 + t, z(t) = 17 + 5t</m>.
        </p>
      </answer>
      <solution>
        <p>
          <m>x(t) = -4 - 2t, y(t) = 2 + t, z(t) = 17 + 5t</m>.
        </p>
      </solution>
    </task>
    <task>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Show that the two lines intersect at a single point by finding the values of <m>s</m> and <m>t</m> that result in the same point. Then find the point of intersection.  
        </p>
      </statement>
      <answer>
        <p>
          <m>s = 2, t = -2</m>. The point of intersection is <m>(0, 0, 7)</m>.
        </p>
      </answer>
      <solution>
        <p>
          Write a system of two equations by setting the first two corresponding parametric equations equal to each other for each line <m>4 - 2s = -4 - 2t, -2 + s = 2 + t</m>. Solve to get <m>s = 2, t = -2</m>. Plug <m>s = 2</m> or <m>t = -2</m> into either set of parametric equations to get the point <m>(0, 0, 7)</m>. 
        </p>
      </solution>
    </task>
    <task>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Find the acute angle formed where the two lines intersect, noting that this angle will be given by the acute angle between their respective direction vectors.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <answer>
        <p>
          The angle formed where the two lines intersect is <m>12.60^{\circ}</m>.
        </p>
      </answer>
      <solution>
        <p>
          The angle between the unit vectors is <m>\theta = \cos^{-1}\left(\frac{\vu\cdot\vv}{|\vu||\vv|}\right) = \cos^{-1}\left(\frac{(-2)(-2) + (1)(1) + (3)(5)}{|\sqrt{14}||\sqrt{30}|}\right) = 12.60^{\circ}</m>.
        </p>
      </solution>
    </task>
    <!-- <task>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Find an equation for the plane that contains both of the lines described in this problem.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <answer>
        <p>
          <m>2(x - 4) + 4(y + 2) = 0</m> or <m>2(x + 4) + 4(y - 2) = 0</m> or <m>2x + 4y = 0</m>.
        </p>
      </answer>
      <solution>
        <p>
          Find the normal vector to the two direction vectors. <m>\vu \times \vv = ((1)(5) - (3)(1))\vi - ((-2)(5) - (3)(-2))\vj + ((-2)(1) - (-2)(1))\vk = \langle 2, 4, 0 \rangle</m>. Use either <m>(4, -2, 1)</m> or <m>(-4, 2, 17)</m> and <m>\langle 2, 4, 0 \rangle</m> to write the scalar equation of the plane <m>2(x + 4) + 4(y - 2) + 0(z - 17) = 2(x + 4) + 4(y - 2) = 0</m> or <m>2(x - 4) + 4(y + 2) + 0(z - 1) = 2(x - 4) + 4(y + 2) = 0</m>
        </p>
      </solution>
    </task> -->
  </exercise>
  
